{"key":"post-17771371","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17771371</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Colonizes extremely fast, produces huge yield and is strong against contamination. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Apparently you haven't used any other grain yet if you feel this way.&amp;nbsp; Popcorn does not colonize fast.&amp;nbsp; The kernels are huge, so a jar of popcorn has less than half the mycelium of a jar of rye, oats, millet, etc.&amp;nbsp; Thus when a 'jar' colonizes a few days faster but has only half the mycelium, it's actually slower.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Popcorn does not increase yield over other grains.&amp;nbsp; It is the &lt;i&gt;most prone&lt;/i&gt; to contamination of all the grains, probably again due to the large kernel size which leads to insufficient sterilization.&amp;nbsp; Use it as a last resort if nothing else is available, but certainly not as a grain of choice where reliable spawn media is available.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17772216</next>\n<prev>17770997</prev>\n<first>17770878</first>\n<last>17772594</last>\n<when>1360413881</when>\n<utime>02/09/13 02:44 PM</utime>\n</post>"}